# Chapter 4 — Lists

The pair — a cons cell — is the compound data structure Scheme is built around. A list is a nested pair whose last cdr is `()`. Motoi Scheme also lets you use JS arrays under the hood, but the language sees them all as lists.

## Constructing

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(list 1 2 3)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(cons 0 (list 1 2 3))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(range 0 5)
</pre>

## Deconstructing

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(car (list 1 2 3))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(cdr (list 1 2 3))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(cadr (list 'a 'b 'c))
</pre>

## `map`, `filter`, `reduce`

The three that carry ninety percent of list code.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(map (lambda (n) (* n n)) (list 1 2 3 4 5))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(filter (lambda (n) (> n 2)) (list 1 2 3 4 5))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(reduce + 0 (list 1 2 3 4 5))
</pre>

> **Sakura says**
>
> Ever notice how many bugs vanish once you learn to reach for `filter` instead of a hand-rolled loop? I do — mine did too.

